# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computer-vision
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] 2D to 3D conversion adds the binocular disparity depth cue to digital images perceived by the brain, thus, if done properly, greatly improving the immersive effect while viewing stereo video in comparison to 2D video.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] However, in order to be successful, the conversion should be done with sufficient accuracy and correctness: the quality of the original 2D images should not deteriorate, and the introduced disparity cue should not contradict other cues used by the brain for depth perception.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] If done properly and thoroughly, the conversion produces stereo video of similar quality to "native" stereo video which is shot in stereo and accurately adjusted and aligned in post-production.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Two approaches to stereo conversion can be loosely defined: quality semiautomatic conversion for cinema and high-quality 3DTV, and low-quality automatic conversion for cheap 3DTV, VOD and similar applications.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Computer-animated 2D films made with 3D models can be re-rendered in stereoscopic 3D by adding a second virtual camera if the original data is still available.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] This is technically not a conversion; therefore, such re-rendered films have the same quality as films originally produced in stereoscopic 3D.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Examples of this technique include the re-release of *Toy Story* and *Toy Story 2*.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Revisiting the original computer data for the two films took four months, as well as an additional six months to add the 3D.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] However, not all CGI films are re-rendered for the 3D re-release because of the costs, time required, lack of skilled resources or missing computer data.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] With the increase of films released in 3D, 2D to 3D conversion has become more common.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The majority of non-CGI stereo 3D blockbusters are converted fully or at least partially from 2D footage.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Even *Avatar*, notable for its extensive stereo filming, contains several scenes shot in 2D and converted to stereo in post-production.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Even in the case of stereo shooting, conversion can frequently be necessary.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Besides hard-to-shoot scenes, there can be mismatches in stereo views that are too big to adjust, and it is simpler to perform 2D to stereo conversion, treating one of the stereo views as the original 2D source.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] **Filling of uncovered areas** – left or right view images show a scene from a different angle, and parts of objects or entire objects covered by the foreground in the original 2D image should become visible in a stereo pair.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Sometimes the background surfaces are known or can be estimated, so they should be used for filling uncovered areas.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Otherwise the unknown areas must be filled in by an artist or inpainted, since the exact reconstruction is not possible.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Most semiautomatic methods of stereo conversion use depth maps and depth-image-based rendering.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The idea is that a separate auxiliary picture known as the "depth map" is created for each frame or for a series of homogenous frames to indicate depths of objects present in the scene.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The depth map is a separate grayscale image having the same dimensions as the original 2D image, with various shades of gray to indicate the depth of every part of the frame.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] While depth mapping can produce a fairly potent illusion of 3D objects in the video, it inherently does not support semi-transparent objects or areas, nor does it represent occluded surfaces; to emphasize this limitation, depth-based 3D representations are often explicitly referred to as 2.5D.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] These and other similar issues should be dealt with via a separate method.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Image segmentation, creation of mattes or masks, usually by rotoscoping.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Each important surface should be isolated.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The level of detail depends on the required conversion quality and budget.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Each isolated surface should be assigned a depth map.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The separate depth maps should be composed into a scene depth map.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] This is an iterative process requiring adjustment of objects, shapes, depth, and visualization of intermediate results in stereo.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Depth micro-relief, 3D shape is added to most important surfaces to prevent the "cardboard" effect when stereo imagery looks like a combination of flat images just set at different depths.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Stereo generation based on 2D+Depth with any supplemental information like clean plates, restored background, transparency maps, etc.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] When the process is complete, a left and right image will have been created.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Usually the original 2D image is treated as the center image, so that two stereo views are generated.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] However, some methods propose to use the original image as one eye's image and to generate only the other eye's image to minimize the conversion cost.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] During stereo generation, pixels of the original image are shifted to the left or to the right depending on depth map, maximum selected parallax, and screen surface position.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Reconstruction and painting of any uncovered areas not filled by the stereo generator.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Stereo can be presented in any format for preview purposes, including anaglyph.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Time-consuming steps are image segmentation/rotoscoping, depth map creation and uncovered area filling.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The latter is especially important for the highest quality conversion.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] There are various automation techniques for depth map creation and background reconstruction.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] For example, automatic depth estimation can be used to generate initial depth maps for certain frames and shots.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] People engaged in such work may be called depth artists.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] A development on depth mapping, multi-layering works around the limitations of depth mapping by introducing several layers of grayscale depth masks to implement limited semi-transparency.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Similar to a simple technique, multi-layering involves applying a depth map to more than one "slice" of the flat image, resulting in a much better approximation of depth and protrusion.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The more layers are processed separately per frame, the higher the quality of 3D illusion tends to be.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] 3D reconstruction and re-projection may be used for stereo conversion.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] It involves scene 3D model creation, extraction of original image surfaces as textures for 3D objects and, finally, rendering the 3D scene from two virtual cameras to acquire stereo video.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The approach works well enough in case of scenes with static rigid objects like urban shots with buildings, interior shots, but has problems with non-rigid bodies and soft fuzzy edges.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Another method is to set up both left and right virtual cameras, both offset from the original camera but splitting the offset difference, then painting out occlusion edges of isolated objects and characters.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Essentially clean-plating several background, mid ground and foreground elements.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Binocular disparity can also be derived from simple geometry.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] It is possible to automatically estimate depth using different types of motion.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] In case of camera motion, a depth map of the entire scene can be calculated.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Also, object motion can be detected and moving areas can be assigned with smaller depth values than the background.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Occlusions provide information on relative position of moving surfaces.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Approaches of this type are also called "depth from defocus" and "depth from blur".
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] DFD only needs two or three at different focus to properly work, whereas DFF needs 10 to 15 images at least but is more accurate than the previous method.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] If the sky is detected in the processed image, it can also be taken into account that more distant objects, besides being hazy, should be more desaturated and more bluish because of a thick air layer.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The idea of the method is based on the fact that parallel lines, such as railroad tracks and roadsides, appear to converge with distance, eventually reaching a vanishing point at the horizon.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] Finding this vanishing point gives the farthest point of the whole image.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The more the lines converge, the farther away they appear to be.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] So, for depth map, the area between two neighboring vanishing lines can be approximated with a gradient plane.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] PQM mimic the HVS as the results obtained aligns very closely to the Mean Opinion Score (MOS) obtained from subjective tests.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The PQM quantifies the distortion in the luminance, and contrast distortion using an approximation (variances) weighted by the mean of each pixel block to obtain the distortion in an image.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] This distortion is subtracted from 1 to obtain the objective quality score.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] HV3D quality metric has been designed having the human visual 3D perception in mind.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] It takes into account the quality of the individual right and left views, the quality of the cyclopean view (the fusion of the right and left view, what the viewer perceives), as well as the quality of the depth information.
[src:computer-vision/2d-to-3d-conversion] The VQMT3D project includes several developed metrics for evaluating the quality of 2D to 3D conversion based on the cardboard effect, edge-sharpness mismatch, stuck-to-background objects, and comparison with the 2D version.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:computer-vision/3d-model] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] In computer vision, **3D object recognition** involves recognizing and determining 3D information, such as the pose, volume, or shape, of user-chosen 3D objects in a photograph or range scan.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Typically, an example of the object to be recognized is presented to a vision system in a controlled environment, and then for an arbitrary input such as a video stream, the system locates the previously presented object.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] This can be done either off-line, or in real-time.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] The algorithms for solving this problem are specialized for locating a single pre-identified object, and can be contrasted with algorithms which operate on general classes of objects, such as face recognition systems or 3D generic object recognition.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Due to the low cost and ease of acquiring photographs, a significant amount of research has been devoted to 3D object recognition in photographs.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] The method of recognizing a 3D object depends on the properties of an object.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] For simplicity, many existing algorithms have focused on recognizing rigid objects consisting of a single part, that is, objects whose spatial transformation is a Euclidean motion.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Two general approaches have been taken to the problem: pattern recognition approaches use low-level image appearance information to locate an object, while feature-based geometric approaches construct a model for the object to be recognized, and match the model against the photograph.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] These methods use appearance information gathered from pre-captured or pre-computed projections of an object to match the object in the potentially cluttered scene.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] However, they do not take the 3D geometric constraints of the object into consideration during matching, and typically also do not handle occlusion as well as feature-based approaches.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] See [Murase and Nayar 1995] and [Selinger and Nelson 1999].
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Feature-based approaches work well for objects which have distinctive features.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Thus far, objects which have good edge features or blob features have been successfully recognized; for example detection algorithms, see Harris affine region detector and SIFT, respectively.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Due to lack of the appropriate feature detectors, objects without textured, smooth surfaces cannot currently be handled by this approach.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Feature-based object recognizers generally work by pre-capturing a number of fixed views of the object to be recognized, extracting features from these views, and then in the recognition process, matching these features to the scene and enforcing geometric constraints.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] As an example of a prototypical system taking this approach, we will present an outline of the method used by [Rothganger et al.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] The method starts by assuming that objects undergo globally rigid transformations.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Color information is used also to improve discrimination over SIFT features alone.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Next, given a number of camera views of the object (24 in the paper), the method constructs a 3D model for the object, containing the 3D spatial position and orientation of each feature.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Because the number of views of the object is large, typically each feature is present in several adjacent views.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] The center points of such matching features correspond, and detected features are aligned along the dominant gradient direction, so the points at (1, 0) in the local coordinate system of the feature parallelogram also correspond, as do the points (0, 1) in the parallelogram's local coordinates.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Thus for every pair of matching features in nearby views, three point pair correspondences are known.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Given at least two matching features, a multi-view affine structure from motion algorithm (see [Tomasi and Kanade 1992]) can be used to construct an estimate of points positions (up to an arbitrary affine transformation).
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] The paper of Rothganger et al. therefore selects two adjacent views, uses a RANSAC-like method to select two corresponding pairs of features, and adds new features to the partial model built by RANSAC so long as they are under an error term.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Thus for any given pair of adjacent views, the algorithm creates a partial model of all features visible in both views.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] To produce a unified model, the paper takes the largest partial model, and incrementally aligns all smaller partial models to it.
[src:computer-vision/3d-object-recognition] Global minimization is used to reduce the error, then a Euclidean upgrade is used to change the model's feature positions from 3D coordinates unique up to affine transformation to 3D coordinates that are unique up to Euclidean motion.
