[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] Active methods, i.e. range data methods, given the depth map, reconstruct the 3D profile by numerical approximation approach and build the object in scenario based on model.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] These methods actively interfere with the reconstructed object, either mechanically or radiometrically using rangefinders, in order to acquire the depth map, e.g. structured light, laser range finder and other active sensing techniques.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] A simple example of a mechanical method would use a depth gauge to measure a distance to a rotating object put on a turntable.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] More applicable radiometric methods emit radiance towards the object and then measure its reflected part.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] Examples range from moving light sources, colored visible light, time-of-flight lasers to microwaves or 3D ultrasound.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] Passive methods of 3D reconstruction do not interfere with the reconstructed object; they only use a sensor to measure the radiance reflected or emitted by the object's surface to infer its 3D structure through image understanding.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] Typically, the sensor is an image sensor in a camera sensitive to visible light and the input to the method is a set of digital images (one, two or more) or video.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] In this case we talk about image-based reconstruction and the output is a 3D model.
[src:computer-vision/3d-reconstruction] By comparison to active methods, passive methods can be applied to a wider range of situations.
